<br>
1. Charm <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> is</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> a very powerfull tool, with very lethal side effects. This cannot be disputed, as at some point or another, an enchanter/druid/necromancer will bust out their charm spells, and fry things with greater ease than they can do straight up. In fact, Charm is better than Mezing, as you turn the damage around on the add and kill faster than before.<br>
<br>
2. Dire Charm is quite powerfull, almost overpowered (and would be if it were given to any character under 59). After all, how often does one come up against a dispelling mob that will target your pet in order to dispell a charm? How about comming across a dispelling mob in the first place? Those're about as rare as Magicians, it seems.<br>
<br>
I had more, but got distracted. Basically, it's been my experience that many enchanters are Prima Dona's (however it's spelled), and to discount Charm's strength so blatantly is as bad as a Magician ignoring the fact that once charm breaks, the enchanter will be recieving a beatdown unless he/she has cover. However, as level 60 enchanters solo quite effectively with charmies that're level 50+, even taking into account charm breaking, it could be used if so desired.<br>
<br>
I'm sorry you felt bullied into removing the post, Noonie. Charm itself is not overpowered due to the drawbacks and unpredictability. Dire Charm might be, but that's a topic hashed and rehashed quite often. <p><A HREF="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=52886">Rhasin Firestorm</A><BR>
