You posted the facts...ya shouldn't be ashamed of that just because some random n00bie enchanter who doesn't know how to play their class feels threatened. Or..maybe they do know, but don't want a nerf.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Noonie being 'bullied' into removing her post? She posts a controversial trolling post filled with misfacts and exaggerations into trying to show a skill as overpowered and not expect to get some negative feedback from the class she is bashing? She is <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>   not</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> an enchanter. She is a <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>   mage</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> playing an enchanter mule to find faults with the class by looking at the class from a mage perspective. She has been on the enchanters case forever no matter what ability they have. She even thinks our <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>   animation pets</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> are overpowered, because she believes enchanters shouldn't have any offensive ability at all and is only played for crowd control and buff whoring.  Sorry but I can't take a person who thinks our animations are overpowered very seriously as a knowledgeable EQ player. If Noonie was not a mage, she wouldn't be getting the support she has been getting from some mages here for her constant nerf calls of other classes. If she was a druid main with an enchanter alt instead, would her comments be listened to by mages?<br>
<br>
As for the so called n00bie enchanter talk, check my level and the levels of most enchanters that posted in defense of their class. Most are higher level then your mage and even your bard. You have a 59 bard. Charm for bards and enchanters use different mechanics, and can't be really compared eye for eye.<br>
<br>
Now for the real facts about its power instead of biased mumbo jumbo. Charm is the most powerful offensive skill in the game. It has always been that way since the spell was introduced. Used properly, there is no other class then the enchanter that can kill a mob as quickly as a charmed mob can. The enchanter is not known as an offensive oriented class, but in situations becomes a great damage dealer with indirect damage. Charm is so powerful in fact, that I used it to kill an even con at level 58. Simple fact is, the enchanter is one of the premier solo classes after about level 44, and with practice, can outsolo a mage in the 50s. Yes, I am telling you under the right circumstances I can outsolo a mage of the same level. Charming does become more efficient as you gain levels.<br>
<br>
Now here is what the risks lies. The main issue with charm is that if you are charming a mob, you have to face the possiblity that you will at some point end up having 2 mobs on you at any time. If you want damage, you have to realize that the damage you are dealing with your charmed pet can be turned into damage dealt to you in a second. If you choose to haste a mob that hits for 100s, you do so knowing that at some point, you will have to face that hasted mob along with the mob you engaged. If you choose to make the pet dual wielding you have to face the fact that one resist or on a spell or a bad charm break means you die in 5-10 seconds as you can be dealt 400+ damage in one round. The higher the damage you want, the higher the risk of death becomes. Charming requires quite a bit of mana, and chances are your charm will not last the full duration. There are more chances of blowing 1200 mana for casting charm 3 times on a mob that broke 15 seconds after casting then there are for a mob to stay charmed for 8 min.<br>
<br>
When charm soloing you have to take into the fact that the game has the tendency to have charm and root on a mob break at the same time (every enchanter can attest to this). And you won't always have open fields like Dreadlands (which I add is a ridiculously easy zone and should not be used as an example for charm soloing since every class has it easy here) and sow to avoid mobs when it happens. You are not garanteed of not getting any resists on your spells. There is no afk break when charm soloing. You have to be ready for anything that can go wrong and have an escape plan.<br>
<br>
Just as an FYI, the way that Noonie described for soloing is not an effective way to gain solo exp. You kill mobs very fast yes, but you take a 50% exp hit on all the mobs. The mage can outdamage his pet if he wants, the enchanter can't. So while the enchanter can kill a mob fast he has to kill 2 mobs faster then other classes can kill one to match the exp. This type of soloing is mainly used for farming, holding camps or taking on large targets. The real way to gain exp while charming is to charm a mob, send it against an even strength mob, have the mobs fight each other until both only have a sliver of health left, break charm, nuke mob 1, nuke mob 2, get full exp on 2 mobs. Much more efficient. Druid and wizards quad kiting still get more exp per time spent though.<br>
<br>
Charm is a powerful tool when used efficiently, but it simply cannot be compared to a mage pet, because they both have very different strengths and weaknesses. A charmed mob can outdamage a mage pet by far, but remember that this 'pet' can be very volatile and doesn't like his master much<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   . The mage pet won't turn on you at least.<br>
<br>
Still can't believe I needed to defend charm here. What's next, animations again?  <p><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=4356">Turonyen - Level 60 Enchanter</a><br>
